{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hawthorne_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205698255/1938010801/0608.xml":{"full_text":"2\nSenate Recession\nProbers Hold Fear\nOs Slump Baseless\nWitnesses Urge Renewed U. S. Spending,\nTax Revision and Trades' Cooperation\nBy ROBERT A. McGILL\n(1.N.5.). Declaring fears of a severe economic breakdown\nare unfounded, members of the Senate Unemployment and\nRelief Committee today proposed a temporary program,\ndesigned to halt the business recession.\nBased on the first week of tes\ntimony into causes of the reces\nsion, by representatives of busi\nness, industry, labor and the gov\nernment, the verbal recommenda\ntions call for increased Federal\nspending, revision of taxes and\ncloser cooperation between big\nbusiness and the government.\nIn addition members of the com\nmittee stressed the need of a com\nmon ground for Government and\nbusiness to work out their prob\nlems, and proposed that certain\nGovernment and business officials\nadopt a more friendly attitude\ntoward each other.\nBYRNES FOR PEACE\n\"There is no doubt in my\nmind that if big business and\nsome representatives of the Ad\nministration would cease their\nwarfare, the recession would be\nover in a short while,\u201d said Sen\nator Byrnes (D.) of South Caro\nlina, chairman of the committee.\nByrnes' statement placed added\nsignificance to the testimony of\nGen. Robert E. Wood, president of\nSears Roebuck, who declared\nbusiness is holding back in some\ninstances because of the recent at\ntacks by Robert H. Jackson, as\nsistant attorney general and Sec\nretary of Interior Ickes.\nIn agreement with the majority\nof witnesses that have appeared\nbefore the committee, Senator\nMurray (D.) of Montana, urged\nthat additional Government spend\ning be carried out through an ex\npanded PWA program. He rec\nommended in particular that the\nexpansion be devoted mostly to\nirrigation and other forms of land\nconservation in the drought areas.\nASKS MORE PWA\n\"There is a tremendous de\nmand for public works projects,\nwhich will regenerate the\ndraught areas, as well as in\ncrease business and industry,\nand take care of a good deal\nof the unemployment problem,\u201d\nhe said.\nThe majority of representatives\nof business and labor recom\nmended the WPA program be ex\npanded, following testimony of\nMarriner S. Eccles, chairman of\nthe Federal Reserve Board, who\nsaid the Government could \u201cstop\nthe recession\u201d by placing $1,000,-\n000,000 of its sterilized gold in\ncirculation.\nJoining with another majority\nof perons who testified, Murray\nRecommended modification of the\nRax on undistributed corporate\nwarnings, but added he didn\u2019t 'see\npny necessity for repeal of the\nCapital gains tax.\u201d\nNO CAUSE FOR FEAR\nByrnes and Murray both de\nclared there is \u2018\u2018no justification\u201d\nfor the fear psychology witnesses\ntestified is accompanying the re\ncession.\nThe committee, meanwhile, has\nscheduled Lammot duPont, chair\npan of E. I. duPont Nemours\nCompany, as the first witness\nMonday. During the week, the\ncommittee wall investigate the tex\ntile and steel and coal industries,\nand unemployment in agriculture.\nAdditional witnesses invited to\nappear include Benjamin Fair\nless, president of U. S. Steel; John\nL. Lewis, head of the CIO: Secre\ntary of Agriculture Wallace, and\nLeonard P. Ayres, economist, of\nbleveland, Ohio.\npublished Dally at 1817 H St, N. W.\nwith Sunday l\u00ab\u00abue aa the Washington\nHerald-Times\nEditorial Business Phono\nR Epublie 1234\nEntered at Pom O//ic\u00ab. Washington.\nD. C\u201e a* eecond-dase mail matter.\nEleanor Patterson Editor and Publisher\nWilli\u2014 C Bheiioa General Manager\nRT ri\u00df\u00dfirn IN WASHINGTON. D. Q\nIUBUBBI\nDally and\nDally Bunday Bunday\ntau |5\u00bb >5lO 110.40\n\u00a3y 1.60 1.60 #2O\nKJIISL. I.JO LM 150\nOn. Wm* 1\u00bb it?\nrates by mail fob Virginia, mabyland.\nWMT VIRGINIA AND NORTH CAROLINA\nDally and\nDally BunA.y Sunday\nr M M-M MW\nIM I M M\nOna Month 90 I- 20\nOTHER BTATXSL CANADA AND MEXICO\nDally and\nDally Bunday Bunday\nOn. T-\u00bb M\u00bb M M 5 M\nBlx Months 8.60 T.#o\n:KJ\u201cMnntta 1\u00bb\u00bb I.M ITS\n.On. Masts -58 -M 1-M\nAty.'Msn. RTTBSCBIPTIONS FAYABLR\nIN ADVANCE\nT\u00bbl*phont REpublic 1334\nAuto Plants\nCall Men\nTo Work\nDETROIT, Jan. 8 (1.N.5.).\nMichigan relief authorities today\nwere faced with the job of pro\nviding a shock absorber\u201d for the\ni back-wash of the recession as two\nmajor automobile companies led\nthe way in the growing \u2018\u2018back to\nwork\u201d movement in the motor in\ndustry.\nTuesday Chrysler Corporation\nwill bring back 55.000 men idle\nsince before Christmas in a pro\nlonged holiday suspension.\nFORD ISSUES CALL\nHenry Ford has issued a call\nfor 40,000 men idle since the holi\nday week to report back to the\nvast River Rouge plant January 17.\nAmong the smaller plants the\nHudson Motor Company provided\nthe biggest sensation with the an\nnouncement that 6,000 men will\nbe rehired to work on the new\nlow-priced Hudson, 112 which\nwent into production this week.\nThese and other moves toward\nbreaking the recession will make\ndeep inroads in the 168,000 men\nthat Governor Frank Murphy said\nhave been thrown out of automo\nbile industry jobs in the past few\nweeks, but relief authorities will\nhave to continue to fight the\ngrowing problem of caring for the\nneedy.\nPARTS MEN IDLE\nThe men called back to their\njobs in the motor industry will not\nbe given pay checks untli they\nhave worked two weeks. The esti\nmated 100,000 men unemployed in\nthe parts plants of the State prob\nably will not go back to work until\ntwo weeks after the automobile\nplans get back into full swing.\nThat the relief problem is acute\nwas indicated yesterday when Gov\nernor Murphy said he plans to go\nto Washington next week to plead\nfor more Federal funds to help the\nState care for its unemployed.\nIn Detroit the relief load was\nbeing increased by a weekly 5,000\nfamilies, and Fisher Lodge, the\nmunicipal shelter for single men,\nis packed with 1,700 unemployed.\nRelief figures show that at present\n25,000 Detroit families are receiv\ning welfare aid.\nCIO Youth Knifed\nIn Market Strike\nKANSAS CITY, Mo., Jan. 8\n(I.NJs.).\u2014Lyle Lincoln, 21, was\nstabbed yesterday as members of\nthe ClO's United Produce Hand\nlers went out on strike at the city\nmarket. Lincoln, a member of the\nCIO union, was taken to General\nHospital, where his condition was\npronounced critical. Police arrest\nHarold Mitchell, 26, who denied\nany connection with the attack.\nU. S. War Supply Sales\nTo Alien Nations Fall Off\n(1.N.5.) Foreign purchases of\nAmerican-made war supplies\ndropped to the lowest figure of\nthe past 18 months during Decem\nber. The monthly report of the Na\ntional Control Board revealed to\nday, showed a total of $1,930,747.\nThe drop in China\u2019s purchases\nwas the most noteworthy. Dur\ning the month China ordered only\n$290,632 In war equipment, com\npared to purchases which have\nrun an average of from one to\nseveral millions a month for many\nmonths. The December pur\nchases were concentrated in ma\nchine guns, hand grenades and\nbombs.\nThe marked drop in purchases\nToday In\nCongress\nSenate\nMeets at 11 a. m.\nResumes debate on anti-lynch\ning bill.\nHouse\nI Not in session.\nSPANISH DYING\nBY HUNDREDS IN\nFLEEING MADRID\nCivilians Perish in Cold\nEscaping Battle\nLONDON, Jan. 8 (1.N.5.).\nRoads leading from Madrid,\nSpain\u2019s beleaguered capital city\nfrom which the govemmnt fled\nmonths ago, resemble the path of\nNapoleon's famous retreat from\nMoscow, the London Daily Sketch\nreported today.\nHUNDREDS FREEZING\nHundreds of men, women and\nchildren, obeying orders to evacu\nate the city, said the Sketch, are\ndying from exposure on frozen\nroads in temperatures below zero.\nBOMBS ALTERNATIVE!\nThe paper said the great trek\nbegan in earnest, with thousands\nstreaming from the city, in the\nteeth of an arctic gale. A Spanish\ngovernment official was quoted as\nremarking:\n\u2018'Their only alternative was to\nbe bombed and shelled out of\nexistence in the big attack\nwhich is pending.\u201d\n'Peace Dream'\nNazi Papers Ridicule\nWilson'B 14 Points\nBERLIN, Jan. 8 (I.N.S.)\u2014The\nNizi press, ever famous for its color\nful language, outdid itself today\nin commemorating the twentieth\nanniversary of publication of\nWoodrow Wil s o n\u2019s \"Fourteen\nPoints.\u201d\nPropaganda Minister Goebbel\u2019s\nnewspaper, Der Angriff, made the\nanniversary occasion for a ghoul\nish burlesque of American condi\ntions, featured by the observation\nthat Wilson\u2019s dream of perpetual\npeace ended with \"65.000 people\nfreezing in the streets of Cleve\nland.\u201d\n\"A year after they were pro\nmulgated,\u201d Der Angriff said,\n\"these flashy fourteen pqints\nproved to be the greatest swindle\nperpetrated in a century. But\noriginally they were so stunning\nand astounding in their promises\nthat they even disarmed the\nactive German army.\u201d\nMorrow Drive\nTo Close Monday\nEffective Monday, Morrow Drive,\nbetween Sixteenth Street and Rock\nCreek Park, will be closed from\n7 a. m. to 4.30 p. m. because of\nblasting operations for the demoli\ntion of Brightwood Reservoir, Act\ning Superintendent of National\nCapital Parks F. T. Gartside, an\nnounced today.\nThe drive will be open every\nevening from 5 to 7 p. m. Mr.\nGartside said, and all day Satur\nday and Sunday. Motorists who\nhave been using Morrow Drive to\nenter Rock Creek Park can use\nMilitary Road instead, Mr. Gart\nside added.\nBARTENDERS MEET\nThe regular Sunday business\nmeeting of Bartenders Union. Old\nLocal 75, will be held at 3 o\u2019clock\ntomorrow afternoon, union offi\ncials announced today.\nfrom the United States was at\ntributed to the Japanese blockade\nof the China coast, which makes\nis exceedingly difficult for war\nsupplies to enter China, and to\nthe fact that China has now\nturned to European countries to\na much greater extent for as a\nsource of war supplies.\nHeavy purchases have been\nmade from Russia, Germany,\nCzechoslovakia and other coun\ntries for shipment to the British\nport of Hongkong.\nJapan, during the month, pur\nchased $250,282 in war supplies.\nA quarter million of this for a\nsingle war plane, believed to be a\nlong range bomber of the most\nrecent type which it is believed\nshe intends copying in her own\nplane factories. The American\nlong-range bombers have a far\ngreater effective range and load\ncapacity than any craft Japan\nis able to produce. It was said\nhere this indicates Japan intends\nbuilding long-range bombers on a\nlarge scale, to carry the war into\ninterior China.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES, SATURDAY, JANUARY 8, 1938\nHail-Fellow-Well-Met, This Man Rivers\n\u25a0Mik\nIflix -F\nw ITL\nOU'\u25a0\u2019,V w\nJ|\nAl\nLAWRENCE \u201cCHIP\u201d ROBERT, secre\ntary of the Democratic national committee,\nmeets Governor E. D. Rivers at the May-\nUSED CAR DEAL\nPUT UP TO U. S.\nDETROIT, Jan. 8 (I.N.S.).\u2014A\nsuggestion that the Government\nbuy up surplus stocks of used auto\nmobiles and turn them into scrap\nmetal for armaments was made\nin the automobile industry today\nas one possible means of breaking\nthe business recession.\nSuch a plan has been under dis\ncussion in trade circles for some\ntime, it was known, but it first\nreached the light of day today\nin formal comment when Ward\u2019s\nAutomotive Reports said:\n\u201cWe suggest the Government\nstart buying surplus and older\nused cars the same way it buys\nsurplus crops, and use the scrap\nmetal obtained for the proposed\narmament building.\u201d\nWard\u2019s, a trade service, gener\nally reflects the attitude of motor\ncar makers.\n\u2018Sitdown\u2019 Forces\nR. I. Relief Vote\nPROVIDENCE, R. 1., Jan. 8 (I.\nN.S.).\u2014Seated in the Senate gal\nleries of the State capitol, 300 la\nbor sympathizers late yesterday\nwitnessed their first victory in a\n\u201csitdown\u201d drive to enforce enact\nment of a 23-point labor legislation\nprogram when the upper house\npassed the $700,000 unemploy\nment relief bill. The measure, hav\ning previously passed the house,\nwas sent to Governor Robert E.\nQuinn for signature.\nWindsors Guests\nOs Maxine Elliott\nCANNES, Jan. 8 (I.NJS.).\u2014The\nDuke and Duchess of Windsor\nwere dinner guests last night of\nMaxine Elliott, famous American\nactress. Other guests who dined\nat Miss Elliott\u2019s beautiful Rivera\nvilla, I\u2019Horizon, included Lloyd\nGeorge, World War Prime Mini\nster of Britain, and Winston\nChurchill, former British chancel\nlor of the exchequer.\nDivorcee Found\nAttacked, Beaten\nSAN ANSELMO, Calif., Jan. 8\n(I.N.S.).\u2014Brutally beaten by a\nmysterious assailant, Mrs. Elsie\nHannan, 35, divorcee, was found\ncritically injured in her apartment\nhere yesterday.\nShe had been criminally at\ntacked. Police connected the at\ntack on her with the similar beat\ning of Mabel Hawthorne, 50-year\nold actress, in San Francisco Mon\nday night.\nCHEMISTS TO MEET\nThe Chemical Society of Wash\nington v meet in the Cosmos\nClub Audi ,rium. January 13, at\n8:15 p. ia. Ben H. Nicolet, retir\ning president of the society, will\nbe the principal speaker.\nInternational News Photo\nflower Hotel, where the Southeastern\nGovernors Conference held a dinner.\nSeven governors were there.\nU.S. Air Force\nRanks First\nIn Efficiency\nThe United States air force, al\nthough outnumbered by five other\nnations, ranks second to none in\nfighting efficiency, the National\nAdvisory Committee on Aeronau\ntics reported last night.\nThe United States has only\n2,200 fighting planes, the commit\ntee reported, as compared with\nRussia\u2019s 7,500, Germany\u2019s 5,500,\nItaly\u2019s 5,000, France\u2019s 4,000 and\nEngland\u2019s 3,500.\nBut the war birds of America\nare far superior in design, speed\nand efficiency to those of other\ncountries and the skill of Amer\nican aviators can be compared\nonly with that of the English, the\ncommittee asserted.\nThe Army will spend nearly\n$90,000,000 on its aerial armament\nin the next fiscal year, the com\nmittee reported. At the end of\n1937, the Army had 1,020 first\nclass fighting ships; 400 others\nin condition to fight and 700 new\nplanes ordered.\nThe Navy with 1,200 first-line\nfighting planes on hand, 600 new\nships ordered at the close of 1937,\nwill spend $7,000,000 less this year\nfor earcraft, but its appropria\ntion will be sufficient to maintain\npresent high standards of effi\nciency.\nSeconds Arrange\nCasanova Duel\nHAVANA, Jan. 8 (I.N.S.).\u2014Sec\nonds met today to arrange details\nof the duel to which Senator Jose\nManuel Casanova, rich sugar man,\nchallenged Manuel Penabas, politi\ncal writer in La Prensa. Casanova\ncharged that Penabas wrote In\njurious articles in the papen, which\nis owned by ex-President Gomez.\nCasanova\u2019s sejretary denied, how\never, that they would fight to\ndeath.\nCensus Shows 12,164 Here\nAre Partially Unemployed\n(Continued from Page 1)\nwas most difficult because of\nmany variable and changing\nfactors. He asserted:\n\u201cIn our report on total un\nemployment we pointed out the\ndifficulties of measuring the\nmarginal group consisting of\nthose who are not regular work\ners for wages.\n\u201cIn the field of partial un\nemployment other factors make\nthe appraisal even more com\nplex. For example, it is difficult\nto get people to understand the\nimportant distinction between\npartial employment and partial\nunemployment.\nGOVERNORS O.K.\nPAY-HOUR IDEA\nBy EDWARD B. LOCKETT\n(1.N.5.) Wage-hour legislation\nadvocates in Congress undeniably\ngained support today in a resolu\ntion adopted by seven Southeast\nern governors meeting here, but\nwere not entirely clear as to its\nmeaning.\nThe resolution, adopted by the\nseven members of the Southeast\nern governors\u2019 conference, after\na two-hour luncheon visit with\nPresident Roosevelt, indorsed the\n\u201cprinciple\" of a \u201cfloor for wages\nand a ceiling for hours.\u201d\nNot one of the governors would\nelaborate on the meaning of this\nresolution. None would commit\nhimself for or against the bill\nnow pending in a House commit\ntee, after the House itself sent\nit back from the floor, except to\npoint to the resolution adopted.\nSo, while the obvious intent\nof the resolution adopted was to\nsquare the governors from Dixie\nwith the President\u2019s demands for\nsupport of wage-hour legislation,\nthe statesmen from the South did\nnot say yea or nay to any specific\nbin.\nGovernors adopting the resolu\ntion, most important of several,\nincluded Graves of Alabama,\nRivers of Georgia, Johnston of\nSouth Carolina. Hoey of North\nCarolina, Browning of Tennessee,\nCone of Florida, and Leche of\nLouisiana.\nNazis Guillotine\nTrio as Traitors\nBERLIN, Jan. 8 (C.T.P.S.).\nThree men were guillotined in\nBerlin yesterday for high treason.\nThey were Joseph Starck, of Co\nlogne, and Otto Demwolff, of Mi\nlitsch, sentenced for betraying\nmilitary secrets, and Herbert Ga\njewski, of Schneidemuhl, for com\nmunicating with foreign agents.\nTREASURY CONDITION\n(1.N.5.) Treasury balance on\nJanuary 6: $2,965,217,059.73; in\nternal revenue, $16,102,133.31; cus\ntoms receipts. $4,538,079.72.\n\u201cMany persons regularly work\nonly part-time and do not need\noi want more work. They are\npartially employed. Others are\nreduced to part-time work by\nforce of circumstances, not by\npersonal limitations or choice.\nThey are partly unemployed.\n\u201cPreliminary analysis indicates\nthat a very considerable num\nber have registered or reported\nthemselves as partially unem\nployed when they clearly belong\nto the group of partly employed\nworkers, and should not have\nincluded themselves In either\nthe voluntary or test census.\u2019*\nTefapAene REpvblie 1334\nCongress Protest\nFaced By Hull on\nPact With Britain\nDemocratic Majority Expected to Put It\nThrough Over Opposition Blocs\nBy ROBERT G. NIXON\n(1.N.5.) Secretary of State Cordell Hull today launched\nthe United States on the most ambitious commercial arrange\nment in its history\u2014a reciprocal trade pact with America\u2019s\nlargest customer, Great Britain\u2014but headed straightaway\ninto a storm of congressional protest.\nFormal proclamation of this\ncountry's intention of negotiating\na reciprocal trade arrangement\nwith Britain aroused an immediate\ndivision of opinion on Capitol Hill.\nCongressional reaction from the\nNew England boot, shoe and tex\ntile centers, from the agricultural\nMiddle West and from Republican\nhigh tariff exponents generally\nwas caustic, but this was countered\nby the heavy Democratic majority\nwhich stuck by Hull and his re\nciprocal trade policy.\nTRADE GAINS CITED\nFor the critics, Hull calmly drew\nattention to the fact that in the\nfirst 11 months of the past year.\nAmerica\u2019s foreign trade increased\nby the staggering total of nearly\none and a half million dollars, to\na large extent the result of the\n16 reciprocal trade pacts already\nin effect.\nIn announcing that a basis has\nbeen reached for the trade negotia\ntions after more than a year of pre\nliminary conversations, the State\nDepartment published a 47-page\nlist of articles imported from the\nUnited Kingdom which will be con\nsidered for tariff reduction.\nExtensive public hearings must\nbe held, in which American in\ndustry will be given full opportun\nity to express their beliefs, open\ning March 14. It is not expected\nthe treaty will be finally signed\nuntil May, or later.\nU. S. SEES VAST MARKET\nIn return for tariff reductions to\nBritain on certain commodities\nwhich the State Department in\nsists will not harm competitive\nAmerican industries, the United\nStates expects to obtain from Brit\nain a huge new market for agri\ncultural products and cattle, as\nwell as manufactured goods.\nMost of these are unable now to\ncompete in the British market\nbecause of high tariffs and quotas\nthe United Kingdom erected sev\neral years ago under the Empire\nagreement to aid its dominions,\nwhose products enter duty free.\nFear was expressed by New\nEngland Congressmen that any\nreduction of tariffs on leather\ngoods and textiles might \u201cruin\u201d\nthese industries, in comment by\nSenator Henry Cabot Lodge,\njr. (R.), of Massachusetts, and\nhis colleague in the House, Mrs.\nEdith Nourse Rogers.\nOn the other hand, Representa\ntive Doughton (D.) of North Caro\nlina said:\n\u201cI have such complete confi\ndence in the good sense and\nwisdom of the public officials of\nthe United States and Great\nBritain, especially Secretary\nHull, that I am willing to risk\nnegotiations. I have no fear\nthat Secretary Hull will enter\ninto any agreement injurious to\nAmerican interests.\u201d\nElsa Maxwell Sued\nFor S3OO Band Bill\nNEW YORK, Jan. 8 (C.T.P.S.).\nThe way William Arnold, bands\nman, looks at it, those who dance\nshould pay the fiddlers. So Arnold\nhas stated suit for S3OO against\nElsa Maxwell, society\u2019s party\npepper-upper, claiming that sum\nas the balance due of $460 prom\nised him when his 15 man orches\ntra played all night at Elsa\u2019s red\nand white ball in honor of Mrs.\nVincent Astor and Beverly Bogert.\nElsa\u2019s attorneys have demanded\ndetails about the alleged services.\n\u2018Agate-Eye\u2019 Signs\nNew Confession\nNORRISTOWN, Pa., Jan. 8.\nWendell Forrest Bowers, 19, has\nsigned a new confession to the\nslaying of Mrs. Wilma V. Carpen\nter, reenacted the crime for Mont\ngomery county authorities and was\nheld without bail on murder\ncharges. District Attorney Fred\nerick B. Smillie said that as a re\nsult of the new confession it would\nnot be necessary to have Mary\nGriffin, 22, identify Bowers as the\nyouth who shot her companion\nand business associate, and at\ntempted to attack her in Mrs. Car\npenter\u2019s Camp Hill, Pa., home.\nJapan Plans\n4-YearWar\nIn China\nTOKYO, Jan. 8 (1.N.5.).\u20140n\nthe announced assumption that\nNippon\u2019s war with China will last\nfour years, Premier Prince Fuml\nmaro Konoye today placed before\nhis cabinet a four-year plan for\nmaintenance of national resources.\nThe cabinet placed the matter\nin the hands of a national plan\nning board which will draft de\ntails for presentation to the Diet\nJanuary 22.\nThis was the latest, and by far\nthe most official, of many recent\nindications that Japan\u2019s govern\nment believes its campaign in\nChina may develop into a long\nconflict of attrition in which its\nresources will be strained to the\nutmost to accomplish Japan's\n\u201cmission\u201d in the Far East.\nForeign observers here also saw\nmore than a hint in this move of\nofficial belief that the Chinese\ncampaign may develop into some\nthing more general. Never for an\ninstant, it is believed, does the\nTokyo government forget the\nmenace of Soviet Russia to the\nwest, with her huge armies and\nher gigantic air force.\nJAPAN,FRANCE\nNEAR CLASH\n(Continued from Page 1)\nwoman was rescued by the French\npolice and the boundary of the\nFrench concession was closed..\nBreaking Japanese regulations,\nrthe Chinese woman crossed the\nBoulevard des Deux Republiques,\nwhich divides Japanese-occupied\nNantao from the French conces\nsion, to draw water from a pump\non the French side of the road. A\nJapanese soldier spied her, ran\nafter her and began to beat her.\nThe Russian volunteer dashed\nto the Chinese woman\u2019s assistance\nbut the wiry little Japanese\nknocked the Russian to the\nground and tried to wrest the\nvolunteer\u2019s rifle from him.\nSOLDIERS GRAB RUSSIAN\nThe Russian jumped up, drew\nhis revolver and pointed it at his\nNipponese adversary, who quickly\nabandoned his belligerent attitude.\nBut 15 more Japanese soldiers\nfrom the boundary patrol rushed\nto the scene, surrounded the Rus\nsian and began dragging him to\nthe Japanese side of the boundary\nline.\nAttracted by the excitement,\nanother Russian volunteer blew\nhis whistle, bringing two French\narmored cars and a whole truck\nload of Russian volunteers to the\nspot.\nAs they took up positions, ready\nfor any eventuality, 100 fresh Jap\nanese troops suddenly appeared\nand the situation had all the ele\nments of a savage battle. But, no\nshots were fired and the French\nand Japanese officials reached an\namicable adjustment.\nADVERTISEMENT\nt- b|\nh .w|\nMother Knotvs\nThat when she was a youngster\nshe took Father John\u2019s Medicine\nfor colds\u2014so now she gives it to\nher little girl to increase resistance\nto colds, and to develop more\nvigorous health.\nIts successful use by millions dur.\ning the past 83 years is a most con\nvincing proof of value. It must be\ngood.","height":"25850","width":"20234"}}
